Wk17 Fluid balance and the GIT: Vomiting and diarrhea 

Monday, July 31, 2017 

7:36 PM 

Briefly describe the normal routes of fluid intake and loss from the body and the normal ranges for each 

Fluid intake: 

-Oral/IV (note water content in food as well), around 2200ml/day, 1500ml from water. Recommended amount of fluid intake is 40ml/kg/day. 

-Metabolic production from respiration, around 300ml/day 

 

Fluid loss: 

-Feces around 200ml 

-Sweat is minimal, but varies around 100ml 

-Urine varies around 1400ml 

-Insensible (undetectable) loss of around 800ml through evaporative loss from respiratory tract and skin 

 

Note that IN = OUT at around 2500ml/day 

 

Lymph flow is around 2.5L/day. 

Glomerular filtration rate  is around 180L/day 

Fluid turnover in the GIT is around 8-9L a day 

 

Briefly describe the net movements of fluid into and out of the GIT at each level. Include ingestion, secretion and absorption 

Into GIT: 

1200ml food and fluid- ingestion 

1400ml saliva 

2500ml gastric juice 

600ml bile 

1500ml pancreatic juice 

1000ml intestinal juice 

 

Total input = 8200ml 

 

Absorption: 

7000ml from small intestine 

1000-5000ml large intestine 

 

Total output = 8000ml 

 

Input - Absorption = Fluid lost in feces 

 

How does water get absorbed? 

-Nutrients and ions are absorbed through transporter proteins, producing osmotic pressure 

-Water flows down this gradient, into epithelial cells and across tight junctions between epithelial cells 

 

Describe the normal process of defecation and maintenance of fecal continence 

In defecation, first rectal distention causes increased pressure. The increased pressure stimulates the intrinsic nerves to increase peristalsis in the sigmoid colon and relax the internal anal sphincter (parasympathetic). The external anal sphincter is under voluntary control.  

 

If the external sphincter relaxes, defecation commences with a straightening of the anorectal angle. If the external sphincter doesn't relax, the urge to defecate is overridden, with the rectum dilating to accommodate increased volume. Note that there is a straightening of the anorectal angle and descent of the pelvic floor during straining.  

 

 

Fecal continence is maintained by the health of the rectum and anal canal, and the proper functioning of the nerves and muscles involved in defecation. The anal sampling mechanism/reflex also plays an important role, in allowing discrimination of fecal contents and thereby enabling voluntary flatulating without the passing of solid feces. 

 

Briefly describe the mechanisms that lead to loss of fecal continence 

Fecal incontinence is a symptom, caused by: 

-Structural anorectal abnormalities eg sphincter trauma, perianal fistula (infected tunnel between skin and anus), rectal prolapse, weakness of the pelvic floor due to surgery or traumatic childbirth 

-Neurological disorders eg multiple sclerosis, spinal cord injury, stroke 

-Altered bowel habits eg diarrhea, inflammatory bowel disease, chronic constipation leading to overflow incontinence, drugs eg orlistat for obesity 

 

Define diarrhea, and describe its triggers and physiologic mechanisms. 

Diarrhea is defined as having more than three loose or liquid bowel movements per day. If caused by infection, diarrhea can be acute/self-limiting. However, it can also be chronic from an underlying disease. There are three main types of diarrhea:  

-Secretory diarrhea caused by eg cholera toxin, stimulating secretion of anions especially Cl-, causing secretion of Na+ for charge balance and hence the osmotic flow of water into the GI tract. This type of diarrhea continues even without oral food intake.  

-Osmotic diarrhea can be caused by the ingestion of excessive sugar, salt, or insufficient absorption (or non-absorbable molecules), where nutrients are left in the lumen. This causes an osmotic pressure drawing water into the lumen, leading to diarrhea. This generally stops when the offending agent is removed. An example is lactose intolerance, in patients who lack the necessary enzymes certain carbohydrates are not broken down in the small intestine and can draw water into the lumen at the colon. This can present as fatty diarrhea/steatorrhea.  

-Exudative/inflammatory diarrhea occurs with the presence of blood and pus in the stool, due to severe infections or food poisoning. Tissue damage reduces absorptive capacity (osmotic diarrhea), and compromises integrity of the mucosal barrier so fluids leak into the lumen. Bacteria cross this breached barrier to perpetuate the inflammatory reaction. Fever and abdominal pain/tenderness are associated with this.  

 

Note:  

-Dysentery involves blood in the stool, due to an invasion of bowel tissue by infection.  

-Hematochezia refers to passage of fresh blood through anus due to lower GI bleeding 

-Hematopapyrus refers to blood noticed on toilet paper, associated with anal fissures, hemorrhoids (swollen and inflamed veins in rectum and anus causing discomfort and bleeding) 

-Melena is the passage of tarry, darker blood associated with upper GIT bleeding eg due to peptic ulcer  

 

Insufficient fiber = type 5 stool 

Mild diarrhea = type 6 stool 

Severe diarrhea = type 7 stool 

 

Describe the triggers and physiologic mechanisms of vomiting 

Vomiting involves: 

1, Nausea in the upper stomach 

2, Retching involving spasmodic respiratory movement against a closed glottis. Antrum of stomach contracts, rest of stomach relaxes.  

3, Vomiting (emesis) involves hypersalivation to lubricate mouth. A deep breath is taken and the glottis is closed. Larynx is raised to open the upper esophageal sphincter. Soft palate raised to close nasal cavity. Retroperistalsis starts to move contents from duodenum to stomach. Diaphragm is contracted downwards with deep breath initially, and esophagus + lower esophagus sphincter opened. Abdominal muscles contract, and coupled with negative thorax pressure stomach is squeezed with closed pyloric sphincter to cause upward vomiting.  

 

Projectile vomiting is common in young children or patients with obstructed pyloric sphincter. Projectile vomiting can occur suddenly without any indication of discomfort or gastrointestinal upset.  

 

How is vomiting controlled? 

Vomition center: This is located in the medulla, with activation of this center ultimately triggering the vomiting reflex. It receives information from the chemoreceptor trigger zone, and afferents from the GIT (distention, irritation), from outside the GIT (eg bile duct), and from other centers in the brain (odors, fear, vestibular disturbance [motion sickness]). 

 

Chemoreceptor trigger zone: outside of the blood-brain-barrier, just under the fourth ventricle, within the brainstem. Chemoreceptors detect multiple chemical emetic stimuli, including emetic drugs (to induce vomiting), uremia, hypoxia and ketoacidosis. Excitatory signals are then sent to the Vomition center.
